lenders.name: JacksonFineArt
lenders.loan_because:
Jackson Fine Art is a well-known fine art photography gallery. They are located in Buckhead, Atlanta’s uptown district. The gallery focuses on contemporary photography, but also offers some vintage prints. Their merchandise includes art, frames and high quality limited edition b ooks that feature reproduced art.

They sell prints from some of the most famous names in fine art photography. Sally Mann, one of the art form’s first stars in the 1970s and 1980s, is just one of the artists whose work is sold in the gallery. Other featured artists include Holly Andres, Sid Avery, Richard Benson and Jack Spencer. While they focus primarily on selling art, the gallery also hosts events and discussions that feature the artists on display. The talks bring the vision of the artist to patrons who attend, allowing them to understand the perceptions expressed in each work.

Jackson Fine Art was started by Jane Jackson in 1990. The gallery quickly became an important voice in both the North American and international markets. The gallery was sold to long-time director Anna Walker Skillman in 2003. Skillman still owns the gallery. Jackson is now the director of the renowned Sir Elton John Photography Collectio n.

Jackson Fine Art participates in various international art fairs. Past fairs include Paris Photo, Art Chicago: The Navy Pier Show, Photo Los Angeles and The Photography Show (AIPAD) in New York and Miami. They also have an impressive client list of institutions, corporate collections and private buyers. The Metropolitan Museum of Art, The High Museum of Art, The Los Angeles County Museum of Art, The Museum of Fine Arts in Houston and The Art Institute of Chicago are among the public institutions who have procured art from the gallery.

Jackson Fine Art is Atlanta's go-to destination for contemporary fine art photography. Furthermore, the gallery has an extensive stock of fine art photography from other eras. The gallery maintains several active pages on social media, including both Twitter and Facebook. Their blog is also updated reg ularly with links to news stories, information about artist talks, and promotions for photographers who are working in the art.
